caption: Tabor is my favorite Ethiopian restaurant in Baltimore. Food is yummy! Employees are friendly and treat customers well. I recommend this place to enjoy Ethiopian.

Special tibs are perfectly done and are the star of the show. Flavorful, with just the right amount of color. Beets and cabbage are also good. Injera is warm and good for picking up the food. We have been doing carry out with friends during the pandemic and it is nearly as good as dining in house.

First time having Ethiopian food. Definitely an interesting experience! Instead of utensils, you use the injera to pick up the toppings. I’m not sure what it’s supposed to taste like but I imagined it being more spiced and aromatic. It was okay. I felt like I was just eating a bunch of different things.  Maybe I should try it again elsewhere. We also got sambusas to go. Those were a lot better as far as flavor goes.

Best Ethiopian food I have EVER had. Blows away all the restaurants in DC. The food was fantastic, we had a mix of both vegetarian and meat options with our injera. There was a powdered spice that we mixed a little with our dish. I wouldn't have too much of it--it doesn't taste great on its own.

Always go here for Ethiopian food. I really miss the jazz jam sessions but I understand with Covid. The sambusas are out of this world. Never had one served with a sauce before I came here but I like their dipping sauce. Some type of Chipotle mayo? Couldn't quite put my finger on it but it's delicious. If your food is served with injera, don't ask for silverware, it's meant to be eaten with your hands, respect the culture.

The ordering started and I knew exactly what I wanted!! The veggie platter of course. Fast forward to the food arriving!! Well I was smiling from ear to ear because it looked and smelled DELICIOUS! I like Ethiopian cuisine, but I so seldom get to actually eat it, so when we found out there was a place just a few blocks north of where we were staying we had to go. First and foremost, you cannot beat the price. We got a platter that fed 2-3, and as we're all bigger folks, I was a little concerned it wouldn't feed us all. But boy was I wrong. It was basically $10 each and we were all sufficiently full AND took home a full container of the leftovers too. We even got extra injera for free. And there's a great assortment of flavor when it comes to the cuisine. No two items will taste alike, but their flavors can blend together to make something new from the components. I was especially fond of the roasted beets, the collards, and the seared lamb. If you're in the area, check it out, it's worth the visit.

The food was phenomenal as usual.  This is a family owned business as far as I'm concerned, so having been in the restaurant business myself I know that it costs a lot to have many people on staff especially if the profit margins are low. There have been times that it has taken nearly 40 minutes to receive my food but that's usually when the restaurant is at full capacity, the wait for the food is still worth it as the food is always of good flavor and quantity. There is usually only one server who is also the bartender and that means you are not going to get their undivided attention during the busy hours. Even corporate restaurants with many servers have slow service when they are at full capacity and sometimes jeopardize the quality of the food. If you like Ethiopian food or like trying out different cuisine give this small restaurant business a chance

The atmosphere is kind of like a dive bar, with its cheap plastic tablecloths, neon lit bar, cheap menus, and dark lighting. The air was thick with incense when we went, and Ethiopian music plays in the background, so it sweeps you away from the rough street feel outside. The server is friendly and speaks very good if heavily accented English.  I start with all this to lead to this point: Don't let any of this put you off! The food is in a word splendid. We got the Baltimore platter and every bite was perfectly seasoned, cooked to perfection, and bursting with amazing flavor. The meats were crispy, even on sauce, and everything was fresh, no taste of staleness or having sat under a lamp. This place is a hidden gem for anyone craving Ethiopian food.

I visited Tabor Ethiopian as part of Baltimore's Vegan Weekend in February. The menu looked great, and we were excited. Things didn't go as planned. We were seated at a table that hadn't fully been cleaned. The server (only one working the floor at the time, as far as I could see) forgot about my husband's drink order, and took a long time to come around to get our dinner order.  We'd been seated at least 30 minutes by the time our appetizer (Veggie Sambusas) arrived. While they tasted great, the middles were still partially frozen. I called the server over to our table, and she literally told me that, no, they weren't cold in the middle. We had to insist that she put her finger in the middle of one to feel before she'd believe us, and asked that she bring out a fully-cooked, new order. She reluctantly took them back to the kitchen, but then brought out the same plate a few minutes later, including the sambusa she's stuck her finger in. At this point, we were so frustrated we decided to leave. We firmly but politely told the server we were leaving and why, and asked for the check for my husband's beer. She didn't understand, and eventually got her manager (another few minutes). He tried to get us to stay as well, didn't seem too concerned about the terrible service, and wouldn't bring us the check, said that our food was almost ready, and told us to wait, walked off. We left some cash for the beer, and walked out.  Awful service, would not recommend!
